<h1>Example 1</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">The most common use of semicolons is for linking two independent clauses. This usage can also include a transitional phrase. Common transitional phrases are: however, moreover, therefore, and otherwise; however, a transitional phrase is not required, and a semicolon alone is enough to join two independent clauses. When using a transitional phrase, it should be followed with a comma.</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The patient's overall condition had improved greatly<span class="red">, however</span> the doctor's still wanted the patient to stay overnight for continued observation.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example is in fact a run-on sentence due to the improper use of a comma. When joining independent clauses, commas must be accompanied by a coordinating conjunction. With transitional phrases such as "however," we need to employ a semicolon.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The patient's overall condition had improved greatly<span class="green">; however,</span> the doctor's still wanted the patient to stay overnight for continued observation.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">The sentence is corrected by replacing the comma before our transitional phrase with a semicolon and adding a comma after our transitional phrase. </p>
