</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The hospital's child care center is one of the most well respected in the country. Parents come from around the world seeking out the best care for their children.</h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example is in fact correct. We are given two complete sentences, seperated by a period. Whether we want to use a semicolon to join these sentences is a matter of preference. Typically semicolons are used when the writer wants to emphasize the link between two sentences.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The hospital's child care center is one of the most well respected in the country; parents come from around the world seeking out the best care for their children.</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">By replacing our period with a semicolon, we change our sentence into a grammatically correct compound sentence. Notice how the addition of the semicolon emphasizes the connection between the two sentences' meanings.</p>
